Reproducible Research Project: Technical and Humanities Students’ Perspectives on the Development and Sustainability of Artificial Intelligence (AI)

Szymon Karkoszka, Antoni Piotrowski

  1. Why it is important to reproduce the paper — problem description and topic importance

The perception of students on AI in education is a crucial topic to analyze from an economic standpoint. The incorporation of AI in the education sector has been increasing in recent years, with the emergence of smart classrooms and personalized learning platforms. The potential benefits of AI in education include improved learning outcomes, increased accessibility, and efficiency gains in educational delivery. Understanding the perceptions of students towards AI in education is vital to inform policies and investment decisions in the education sector. The analysis of student perceptions can provide insights into the potential barriers and facilitators to AI adoption in education, as well as inform strategies for the development of AI technologies that are sensitive to student needs and concerns.

This paper aims to analyze students’ perception on the AI in Education. Therfore we decide to examine the differences between the studies.

  1. Data In terms of the comparison, the data we found are excellent as they both compare student and both from Romania. Unfortunately, our data set is 10 times smaller but much more informative. Our data are also much more up to date and we can say that we compare data between two “AI Waves” — one from 2017 and another from 2022.

The dataset utilized in this study encompasses the responses obtained from a survey administered to undergraduate students in their 2nd and 3rd years of study at the Faculty of Cybernetics, Statistics, and Economic Informatics. The survey was conducted online and disseminated through social media groups. Its objective was to acquire insights into students’ perceptions regarding the role of artificial intelligence (AI) in the domain of education.

This dataset comprises a total of 96 observations, each representing a unique case or participant. Additionally, the dataset contains 36 variables, which encompass the different characteristics or attributes under investigation.

Creating data frame with sources of students’ knowledge with their counts and producing an appropriate plot

Comparison with the paper: A first perspective they identify how well the respondents understood the concept of artificial intelligence. Their results show that 84.6% consider that they know what artificial intelligence means, whereas 12% claim that they do not know what the concept means. At the same time, 3.4% answered “I don’t know/I won’t answer”

The highest percentage belongs to the category of those who believe that they have an average awareness of artificial intelligence (36.1%). By referring to this average category, while cumulating two other answers (very well informed, 2.4%, and well informed, 16.8%), which represent the number of those with an above-average level of awareness, as well as cumulating the remaining two answers (poorly informed, 35%, and very poorly informed, 9.7%) which represent the category of those with a below-average level of awareness, showing that the number of those who consider themselves less informed is greater than the category of those who believe that they are well informed on the subject (44.7% as opposed to 19.2%).

Relation with student’s knowledge about AI

# Define the columns vector
columns <- c("Q2.1.Internet", "Q2.2.Books.Papers", "Q2.3.Social_media", "Q2.4.Discussions", "Q2.5.NotInformed")

# Create an empty list to store the results
results <- list()

# Iterate over the columns
for (i in columns) {
  x1 <- mean(data[data[, i] == 0, "Q1.AI_knowledge"], na.rm = TRUE)
  x2 <- mean(data[data[, i] == 1, "Q1.AI_knowledge"], na.rm = TRUE)
  change <- round(x2 - x1, 2)
  results[[i]] <- c(x1, x2, change)
}

# Create a data frame from the results list
data2 <- data.frame(t(as.data.frame(results)))
colnames(data2) <- c("No - MeanQ1", "Yes - MeanQ1", "Absolute Change")
row.names(data2) <- columns

# Print the resulting data frame

data3 <- data[c('Q1.AI_knowledge', 'Q3.2.Job_replacement', 'Q3.3.Problem_solving', 'Q3.4.AI_rulling_society', 'Q12.Gender')]

data3 <- data3 %>%
  mutate(Q1.AI_knowledge = case_when(
    Q1.AI_knowledge %in% c(1, 2) ~ "very poorly informed/uninformed",
    Q1.AI_knowledge %in% c(3, 4) ~ "poorly informed",
    Q1.AI_knowledge %in% c(5, 6) ~ "sufficiently informed",
    Q1.AI_knowledge %in% c(7, 8) ~ "well informed",
    Q1.AI_knowledge %in% c(9, 10) ~ "very well informed"
  ),
  Q12.Gender = case_when(
    Q12.Gender == 1 ~ 'F',
    Q12.Gender == 2 ~ 'M',
    TRUE ~ as.character(Q12.Gender)
  ),
  Q3.2.Job_replacement = case_when(
    Q3.2.Job_replacement %in% c(1) ~ "Strongly Disagree",
    Q3.2.Job_replacement %in% c(2) ~ "Partially Disagree",
    Q3.2.Job_replacement %in% c(3) ~ "Neutral",
    Q3.2.Job_replacement %in% c(4) ~ "Partially Agree",
    Q3.2.Job_replacement %in% c(5) ~ "Fully Agree"
  ),
  Q3.3.Problem_solving = case_when(
    Q3.3.Problem_solving %in% c(1) ~ "Strongly Disagree",
    Q3.3.Problem_solving %in% c(2) ~ "Partially Disagree",
    Q3.3.Problem_solving %in% c(3) ~ "Neutral",
    Q3.3.Problem_solving %in% c(4) ~ "Partially Agree",
    Q3.3.Problem_solving %in% c(5) ~ "Fully Agree"
  ),
  Q3.4.AI_rulling_society = case_when(
    Q3.4.AI_rulling_society %in% c(1) ~ "Strongly Disagree",
    Q3.4.AI_rulling_society %in% c(2) ~ "Partially Disagree",
    Q3.4.AI_rulling_society %in% c(3) ~ "Neutral",
    Q3.4.AI_rulling_society %in% c(4) ~ "Partially Agree",
    Q3.4.AI_rulling_society %in% c(5) ~ "Fully Agree"))
data3 <- data3 %>%
  mutate(Q1.AI_knowledge = factor(Q1.AI_knowledge, levels = c("very poorly informed/uninformed", "poorly informed", "sufficiently informed", "well informed", "very well informed"), ordered = TRUE))

ordered_levels <- c("Strongly Disagree", "Partially Disagree", "Neutral", "Partially Agree", "Fully Agree")

data3 <- data3 %>%
  mutate(Q3.2.Job_replacement = factor(Q3.2.Job_replacement, levels = ordered_levels, ordered = TRUE))
data3 <- data3 %>%
  mutate(Q3.3.Problem_solving = factor(Q3.3.Problem_solving, levels = ordered_levels, ordered = TRUE))
data3 <- data3 %>%
  mutate(Q3.4.AI_rulling_society = factor(Q3.4.AI_rulling_society, levels = ordered_levels, ordered = TRUE))
knowledge_summary <- data3 %>%
  count(Q1.AI_knowledge) %>%
  rename(Category = Q1.AI_knowledge, Count = n) %>%
  mutate(Percentage = Count / sum(Count))

ggplot(knowledge_summary, aes(x = "", y = Percentage, fill = Category)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", width = 1) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of AI Knowledge Levels",
       x = NULL, y = NULL, fill = "AI Knowledge Level") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank(),
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold")) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "RdYlGn") + 
  geom_text(aes(label = percent(Percentage)), position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))

table_data <- data3 %>%
  group_by(Q12.Gender, Q1.AI_knowledge) %>%
  summarise(Count = n()) %>%
  mutate(Percentage = Count / sum(Count) * 100) %>%
  arrange(Q12.Gender, Q1.AI_knowledge)

pivot_table <- table_data %>%
  select(-Count) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = Q12.Gender, values_from = Percentage, values_fill = list(Percentage = 0))

pivot_table <- pivot_table %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ paste0(round(.x, 1), "%")))

pivot_table %>% 
  kable( format = "markdown", col.names = c("AI Knowledge Level", "Female (%)", "Male (%)")) %>% 
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE, bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"))
AI Knowledge Level Female (%) Male (%)
very poorly informed/uninformed 1.7% 12.5%
poorly informed 18.6% 12.5%
sufficiently informed 42.4% 28.1%
well informed 32.2% 34.4%
very well informed 5.1% 12.5%
